segments.text: I thought it was mighty good.
I thought the required subjects in English, mathematics, chemistry, biology, those made a very good foundation to build on with more applied subjects.
I never was too favorable to the requirements in history and government.
That's one of my favorite requirements.
Yeah, of course.
There was a gentleman by the name of Paul Pearson who taught nutrition in the animal science department who was really the primary one and inspired me to take graduate work.
And as a junior,
and I did pretty well in his nutrition course.
He had me take an additional course in organic chemistry to prepare for graduate work.
Paul Pearson
very strangely is still operating in the nutrition field today.
He must be mid-seventies or so, but he's associated with the faculty at his medical college at the University of Arizona.
He's the leader in nutrition around.
He left the nutrition section
in the Animal Science Department.
He was the first dean of the Graduate College at Texas A&M, so he was that caliber guy.
So I was just very fortunate in being exposed to really high caliber people as an undergraduate student.
Fred Bryson, who's died last year after he was recognized and received that Distinguished Alumni Award.
just an outstanding person, taught horticulture at that time.
I later was associated with him in the A&M Methodist Church for many, many, many years.
So I was just so fortunate to be exposed to really high caliber, well qualified teachers.
Why did these fine people, why do you think that they took an interest in you?
I think they were interested in all of their students.
I don't say that they were showing favoritism toward me.
I did have a good academic record along.
I think that's the same thing's true today.
The ones that perform well in any course will receive a little increased attention and encouragement from instructors.
Can you tell me about your student colleagues?
You learn quite a bit in the Corps.
Did you learn from them in the classroom?
Well of course.
I just got through talking to one of them a few minutes ago.
It was a high administration of Iowa beef processors by the name of Charlie Jennings.
I remember going through class with him.
Ed Brown still see a good many of the classmates that I went to school with.
They have performed mighty well as a general rule.
Certainly we were stimulated by the association of the people in the classroom and the laboratories.
We live together a lot closer than the students do today.
I would say that we have developed a little closer comradeship than is the usual situation as we go through school.
We were on campus most weekends.
We were interacting a whole lot more.
Smaller student body.
Sure.
Another question about the core.
We were talking before, this is one I forgot to ask you, we were talking before about the opinion of graduates of other ROTC and West Point of Texas A&M Corps officers.
In what way do you think being a member of the Corps helped your career, and in what way did it hinder your career, if there are any ways?
Well, I can dispose of that first.
I don't know any way being a member of the Cadet Corps of Texas A&M ever would have hindered me in any way.
Okay.
I think it helped because Texas A&M had such a fine reputation with the military, which I think it enjoys today.
I think it still has that kind of a reputation.
Well, that was no excuse.
I mean, no substitute for performance, but it sure did give you a leg up.
Sure did.
Being a graduate from ROTC at Texas A&M, you were presumed to be effective as an Army officer right off the bat.
Were there other reasons beside the fact that
you enjoyed the 10 acres at your home and had animals when you were a child.
Were there other reasons beside that that you decided to go into agriculture when you got here?
Well as I told you, I was enrolled in agricultural engineering.
Yeah, when you first came here.
And I'd always enjoyed livestock so much.
Of course I wasn't
employed for pay.
But I spent most of my time around the cattle barn in Texas A&M working for free.
I believe in that.
If a person wants a job, he can show somebody what he can do.
If a job comes up, he can get it.
So actually I didn't get one there.
I got one on the janitor's horse.
So even though I was
registered in agricultural engineering and had an entirely satisfactory academic record in engineering my first semester.
I transferred over the second semester because obviously that's where my major interest was.
I was, as I say, stimulated by my vocational agriculture instructor in high school.
by the county agent for whom I worked one summer, and measuring crop acreages around.
I just enjoy watching things grow, particularly livestock.
From the time I was a little bit kid, I was fascinated with livestock, particularly cattle.
I've had the pleasure of interviewing a number of

associated with the College of Veterinary Medicine here, and it sounds like they had similar experiences in their youth as you have had, and similar interests in livestock and in animals that you had.
Why did you, did you ever consider going into veterinary medicine?
No, I really didn't.
My closest friend from Orange
was a year ahead of me and was in veterinary medicine.
His name was Herschel Darman.
Darman?
Darman, D-O-R-M-A, and still is a veterinary practitioner at Fort Worth.
I don't know why I suppose, you know, my first
major with agricultural engineering, so that was way off the track.
Right.
You know, then I got it.
Herschel Darman, my good friend, worked at the Beef Kettle Center, and I used to help him.
Got acquainted with the people around there, and acquainted with the professors in the Animal Science Department in that way, so I would say, no, I didn't ever consider veterinary medicine, though.
I've always had a respect for veterinary medicine.
Herschel Darman asked me to come with him to anatomy lectures sometime to hear Dr. Mark Francis lecture.
I did that a few times.
Did you really?
Oh yeah.
What did you think of Dr. Francis?
Oh what a great gentleman.
Of course by that time he was deaf.
He had certain eccentricities, but he was devoted to students at Texas A&M.
He was an outstanding person and an outstanding lecturer and certainly had the respect of his students.
And I got acquainted during that time with Dr. Marsh Diller, first dean of Under Medicine.
I cleaned up his office in this building.
He was in this building, you see.
All the deans, the four deans were in this building, so I got acquainted with him.
What type of a man was he?
He was a little bit courtly and a little bit clumsy.
That way, a good scholar.
His wife showed American Saddle Horses, so I got acquainted with her through that means.
Owen Garrigan at the Staples, we used to have horse shows in the Pavilion.
Dr. Leonard over in the Charter Deau Veterinary Laboratories, that is a clinic.
I got acquainted with him, had a lot of respect for him.
We had, let's see, Dr. Pat Burns, who's still around right now.
He taught me veterinary physiology.
Oh, really?
And you know, I thought it was really something when he expected us to know the names of all the 207 bones and body, whatever it was, I guess.
But you know, I did it, whatever it is.
Fine, fine teacher.
Dr. Leonard taught us veterinary.
We had a course for animal scientists in veterinary medicine.
He lectured that way, so I know that I still have a fine respect for veterinarians.
I'm sure that a lot of that was developed during the time I was a student.
primarily because I got associated with them because of my real good friend, Herschel Darman, who was taking winter medicine.
What were your plans when you graduated in 1939?
Well, I sure, first plan was to try to get something to get that job.
A lot of people that graduated in those days couldn't find employment.
A.K.
Mackey was associated with the dining hall and purchasing the meat for them.
After I had a course under him and he got me involved with his research a bit with Sylvia
He also got me acquainted with his extra job of purchasing, providing, consulting with the dining hall on purchasing meat.
But during my senior year, I got acquainted with Cliff Holtard, Jay Penniston, through A.K.
Mikey.
Of course, I wound up then that I got my brother acquainted with him too, and they hired both of us on graduation.
Actually, I started working for the Dining Hall Department a month or two before I graduated.
Went right into that position.
My responsibility was working with Mr. Mikey and making the decisions on meat purchases and advising Cliff O'Tart about that.
So I was the first dining hall steward of Duncan Dining Hall on this campus, which was brand new in the fall of 1939.
And my brother then got acquainted through my early association.
He took a position with the dining hall department.
He was dining hall steward of Sabiza Dining Hall.
So that's what both of us did when we graduated.
We moved right into that position.
Those were good jobs in those days.
They had $125 a month in room and board.
No kidding.
So we were provided quarters over near Hotard Hall.
Hotard Hall was brand new a little later and he and I both lived in Hotard Hall too as bachelors.
A little later we had some wooden quarters right behind the old board of directors' quarters here in those days.
Those were real good jobs.
Even though you had been a regimental commander, then you didn't look forward to a military career?
What were your feelings on a military career?
Well, I had that opportunity.
They kept in garrison while they were OTC instructors.
nominated me or the instructors had for distinguished military graduate.
I believe there were nine in those days.
They were pretty selective.
There were nine distinguished military graduates.
I was one of them.
He talked to me about going into the services.
I did
consider that opportunity.
I think I was too close to family, just too provincial Texan to want to get into a big adventure of getting in the Army and being stationed in some foreign country like Oklahoma.
Or getting all around the world.
I think that's what was
made me a holding all, something like that.
I couldn't see being separated from my family that much.
You were only 20 at this time?
That's right.
Of course I couldn't be commissioned when I graduated.
In those days you couldn't get a commission until you were 21, so I wasn't
commissioned at ROTC, couldn't get my commission.
I had to apply after my birthday, September the 29th of 1939, and I actually received my commission in December.
Because you had to be 21 years old to get a commission.
Some of my classmates did Darcy McCrory, for instance, right here, who's right around Brian, was a distinguished military graduate.
He went right in the armed forces.
He retired as a colonel, came back here and started working.
It's kind of interesting that one of the first people that my father and I
talked to when we came to Texas A&M looking for student employment was a man named Arvin Simpson.
Who of course became a Lieutenant General in the Marine Corps.
Back here he had been for five or six years.
So anyhow.
What impact did Simpson have on you?
Did you know him very well?
Not about any, no.
That's, he was, he was
a fairly recent graduate then and around working in the position.
Lucian Morgan also had gone into insurance.
Sid Loveless was in the insurance business.
He sold me an insurance policy at that time.
He was an outstanding ROTC cadet devoted to the cavalry.
Now he and I share a grandchildren.
My daughter's married to his son.
In other words, when you graduated in 1939, you didn't look forward to a military career.
You made a choice at that time.
That's right, and I certainly, I was interested in a career in Meach at that time, because I was so fascinated with what I'd done with A.K.
Mikey and Sylvia Colbert.
Inspired by that and my opportunity to work with people at Swifton Company and Armoring Company in Fort Worth and other packers, Houston Packing Company.
My intention was, I was very pleased with the opportunity I had to work in the food business in the dining halls.
Cliff Holtard,
was an outstanding man managing the dining halls.
The chefs we had in both Duncan and Savisa Dining Hall were real top people in the food business.
I was satisfied, that looked like a good career to me.
And I lived at Texas A&M, so you know, I'll go get a job right here.
That's right.
Now when you graduated, I know that one of your goals of course was to get a job like you just said.
Did you have other definite goals or were you at the age of 20 not very sure about what you wanted to do in the future?
I certainly wasn't very sure.
The first thing that was essential for me to do was earn a living.
I had
sort of suppressed the desire to take graduate work.
I couldn't see how that could be funded.
So after Paul Pearson inspired me to take organic chemistry to prepare for graduate work, I took the first semester of it.
It was a real demanding course.
Only half the class passed it.
I was in that course with the chemical engineers and others, classical organic chemistry.
I think I made a C in it, I remember for sure.
Anyhow, that worked me harder than I wanted to work, so I didn't take the second semester of it.
But I appreciated the fact that it is very demanding.
When I came back and started graduate work in 1947, I took the second semester of it then, and I couldn't remember enough of the first semester of A&R.
So I lost my ambition to any I might have ever had to do graduate work, because I just couldn't see any financial way of doing it until I graduated.
Of course, the entry in the armed services was entirely accidental.
During that time, we had what was called the Thomason Act.
And as the armed forces started expanding in the late 30s, every reserve officer was obliged to serve one year in the armed forces.
And as they started expanding, they started some, they started the consolidated masses.
They didn't have any large mess halls anywhere in the armed forces then.
And the newest one in the country was Duncan Dining Hall on this campus.
And it was a real well done facility.
Much stainless steel, latest design, a fine food facility.
One of the best in the country at that time, of that nature.
So we had a good many visitors from the armed forces when they were going into consolidated messes around at airfields and some of the army bases were expanding at that time.
One of them was the Commandant of the School for Bakers and Cooks for the Eighth Corps at Fort Sam Houston, Texas.
His name was Wayne M. Pickles.
When I was showing him around the Duncan Nightingale and all, he learned that I had an ROTC commission.
And propositioned me, as he was expanding his operations, to come in to work with him at Fort Sam Houston, the school for bakers and cooks.
In what capacity?
As assistant commandant.
Really?
So I was called in August the 4th, 1941 to serve a year under the Thomason Act as assistant commandant of the school for breakers and cooks at Fort Sam Houston.
So while my branch As a lieutenant?
As a second lieutenant, while my branch was artillery, I was called in at the quartermaster corps.
and functioned.
I taught the meats work and carried out some administrative duties with the school for bakers and cooks at Fort Sam Houston, Texas.
So you took official leave then from A&M?
Took official leave, one year official leave.
Then after Pearl Harbor
Shortly after that, you know, I couldn't quite stand it.
I was shirking my training, I felt like, so I put in for transfer to my basic ranch.
And I was transferred about 200 yards there from the headquarters of the school for bakers and cooks to the old outfit of the second division right there in San Antonio.
They had worked with me in ROTC's.
I must have had one of the shortest distance track for them.
What did you do as far as bakers and cooks?
You trained enlisted men or officers?
We did have officer, we did have mess officer courses, they were shorter, but we trained bakers and cooks.
So it was, I don't remember the length of the course.
Seemed to be like a nine month course early.
You know, as things heated up, it was contracted and concentrated and intensified, but early.
When I first got in the Army, my shots, you know, things were pretty leisurely.
We had Wednesday afternoons off, weekends, so it was a pretty leisurely sort of thing those days.
Wasn't anybody in any hurry.
Nine-month course for Feckerson Cooks.
Where were you in December 7, 1941?
I was right here at College Station.
I started courting Jane Gray, who worked for the dining hall department as a secretary.
She lived right here on campus.
And I believe December 7th was Sunday.
I was enjoying playing golf.
I was over here for the weekend.
I played golf.
And when I heard about it, I was driving back to San Antonio.
I heard about it on the automobile radio on the way back to San Antonio.
I decided right then that I would put in for transfer back to my basic branch for artillery.
Had you been following the news or were you pretty shocked?
Oh I was very very shocked, certainly.
I'd been following the news.
Of course I knew it was developments in Europe and threats around the world.
I sure didn't expect anything like that from the Japanese.
Very few others to talk about.
That's absolutely for sure.
Now next time, we're going to talk about your military career in Dell.
Do you have other appointments right now?
No.
I'd like to ask you just two last questions for this session about Texas A&M before we leave your student years.
How many former students that I've talked to feel that there's something special about A&M?
I always get this, that it's more than an institution of higher learning.
Do you have that feeling, and if you do, could you describe it?
Certainly, I think it is more than an institution of higher learning.
I don't think it is quite as much now with more than 30,000 students as it was when I came here.
It was one big fraternity.
The students considered it that and resisted any offshoots of fraternities at all.
there was a strong military tradition.
I think it was a fraternity of brotherhood, that's what it was, the whole outfit.
And if you,
followed along, accepted the traditions, accepted the hazing, the relationships of freshman and upperclassmen, and all of that.
You earned a position.
You earned a place in the fraternity.
Even to get in a student club like the Silent Sirloin Club, you had to make sacrifices.
You weren't even eligible until you got to be a junior as a major.
Then there was an initiation rite with hazing involved in it.
You had to make sacrifices to belong, so you respected the membership a whole lot more than getting it now, where all you gotta do is pay three dollars or something.
You had to be an animal science major.
It was something to lead to something special.
Well, Texas A&M is something special.
It was just the experiences and the sacrifices made just created a special bond among the students.
This camaraderie you were talking about.
That's right, and the faculty too.
Remember in those days, when I came here, there were I don't know how many houses on campus.
D.W. Williams and A.K.
Mackey lived in houses right on the campus.
So the faculty people were associated with the students to a much greater degree, not only in the classroom but outside the classroom.
You lived together more.
There just weren't all the distractions, we might call them today.
There weren't the opportunities to leave the campus and participate in things.
You just weren't as mobile.
So all of those things, I think, created a much stronger bond.
among the students than at other institutions those days and compared to today.
Those are things that you consider unique then about A&M?
Well certainly, of course, my goodness.
We marched to meals.
We ate together all at one time.
So those things were very unique.
in bonding together, relationship among the students.
You were expected to know traditions, to introduce yourself to everybody as a freshman.
I said there were no disadvantages being an ROTC, and I'm sure that's one right there.
Obviously, when you walked into a group and there were 25 or 30 upperclassmen around, you had to introduce yourself to every one of them.
So I'm sure I developed a terrible habit of not paying any attention to what their names were.
In the office, you couldn't remember them all.
And I think that's a habit I developed that still persists.
I have trouble remembering names of people because of that.
And the Farmer Students Association, they were respected so much.
